LOUISVILLE Cassius Clay,
worlds heavyweight champion,
said he felt safer in Mississippi
than in New York.


After his tour Of Africa, Clay
said injustice to the Negroes Is
not limited to the South. He
felt that the demonstrations such
as sit-ins and stand-ins we're
silly.


Clay continued that four or
five states should be given to
the Negroes for a nation Of their
own. He felt that this would repay
his people for more than 1910
years of labor"


The talkative heavyweight re-
affirmed his affiliation with Eli
iah Muhammad.

Roy L. Elson, administrative
assistant to Senator Carl Hayden,
announced he will seek the Sep
TENDER Democratic nomination
for the United States Senate In
the primary election.


Elson said that he made his de-
cision to run because Of a deep
concern over such Arizona prob
lens as, "the need for more IN
dustry, the need for more jobs,
and the very urgent need for
Colorado River water.


The SO year old Korean War

veteran, who has been Hayden's
right hand man in Arizona S fight
for water, was educated in the
public schools of Tucson, and
graduated from the University of
Arizona. He is married to the
former Minor Boring, a North
Carolina school teacher whom he
met while serving with the United
States Air Force in Europe. They
have two children, Lane, age five,
and Jean, age three. They reside
at 5000 North 9TH Street in Phoe-
nix.

Starting July l, a new admis-
sion rate for swimmers attend
ing after 7 pm. was effective
at Phoenix City pools. The basic
admission of l5&, except at Al
kire, Eastlake, Grant and Hair
mon where the price will be l0&,
will apply to all persons from 7
pm. until closing time.


The change was approved on an
experimental basis by the Phoe-
nix Parks, Fairgrounds and Rec
reational Board at its meeting
of June l8, 1864.


Most pools are open until 9
pm. daily during June, July and
August.

8 bedrooms. Partly furnished.
Large shady lot, ideal for child
rem. Newly decorated. 46l8S. 9th
Place, 96o-03l8 by owner.
